        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 60-year-old farmer presents with pulmonary symptoms including a productive cough and chest pain. A CT scan reveals a cavitary lesion in the upper lobe of the right lung. A sputum sample is obtained, and microscopy shows hyphal elements that fragment into rectangular arthroconidia. Which of the following types of fungal spores is most likely observed under the microscope?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1742159",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 35684,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Arthrospores</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Arthrospores </strong>are <strong>formed by the fragmentation of hyphae into single, rectangular units </strong>that are <strong>resistant and can be inhaled, leading to infection. </strong>This is characteristic of <strong>fungi such as Coccidioides species</strong>, which can cause <strong>pulmonary cavitary lesions </strong>and are often <strong>associated with agricultural work in endemic areas</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Spores produced by Medically Important Fungi</span></span></span></span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/08/screenshot-2024-03-07-103455.jpg\" style=\"height:267px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>B.</strong> <strong>Conidiospores </strong>are <strong>asexual fungal spores </strong>that are <strong>not formed by fragmentation of hyphae </strong>and are typically seen in <strong>molds such as Aspergillus species.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">. <strong>Basidiospores </strong>are produced by <strong>Basidiomycetes</strong>, which <strong>include mushrooms </strong>and are not typically associated with human disease.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">. <strong>Ascospores </strong>are produced within an <strong>ascus by Ascomycetes </strong>and are not typically associated with the direct fragmentation of hyphae.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/08/screenshot-2024-03-07-103700.jpg\" style=\"height:180px; width:700px\" /></span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Apurba Sastry&rsquo;s Essentials of Medical Microbiology 1/e p550, 2/e p589, Ananthanarayan&nbsp;</span></span></strong></span></span><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">9/e p590-91</span></span></strong></p>",
